results.name: a(n) = binomial(2*c-1, c-1) (mod c^4), where c is the n-th composite number.
comment: Composites c where a(n) = 1 could be called "Wolstenholme pseudoprimes". Do any such composites exist?
A necessary condition for c to be a "Wolstenholme pseudoprime" would be that it is a term of A228562 or A267824.
link: Robert Israel, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000
maple: for n from 4 while count < 100 do
mathematica: Table[Mod[Binomial[2 c - 1, c - 1], c^4], {c, Select[Range@ 50, CompositeQ]}] (* _Michael De Vlieger_, Feb 01 2018 *)
program: return binomial(2*c-1,c-1) % c**4 # _Chai Wah Wu_, Feb 02 2018
